##### Types
- Spray irrigation
	- Least water-efficient irrigation system 
	- Requires 40-50psi
	- Significant amount of the water evaporates into the air
		- Arguably the best way to create as much water vapor as possible
		- But it mimics the effects of rain
- Drip systems
	- Design
		- Irrigation controller
			- Manual, battery, digital, smart
			- Some only have 2 programs
				- Suitable for commercial landscapes, 1 turf 1 shrubs
			- Smart controllers can alter their own programs based on CIMIS and weather data
			- Can get rebates for better irrigation controllers
		- Pressure-reducer
			- Most household appliances need 40-60psi
			- Pressure influences the rate of dripping, needs precise control
			- 
		- Filter
		- Point of connection
			- Valve assembly
	- Benefits
		- Uses much less water
	- Issues
		- Can be fussy
		- Non-recyclable
			- Rubber/plastic pipe is necessarily non-recyclable
				- Biodegradeable materials will increase irrigation rate over time due to degradation around drip connections
			- Thermoplastic
			- Biodegradeable material

			- IE grid-based drip will produce grid-based green spots and pale green spots at the center of the cells

## Propagation

#### Stem cutting
- When trying to grow roots, cut directly below a node
	- Meristomatic tissue there will grow roots when planted
- When pruning for aesthetics, you should also cut off the internode space left over because it wll die
	- You can control the growth of a plant by cutting at nodes that are facing in the direction you want
		- If there isn't one just get rid of the branch 
- One leaf can grow 10000 mature cloned plants
- Summer pruning restricts growth
	- Loses a lot of resources with the removed material
- Winter pruning promotes growth
	- Has resources stored, goes into new growth in the spring

###### Trees
- When roots or branch bases are cut, it causes fungal spores to enter the protected areas of the tree, and will typically kill it in 10 year or so
	- Have to cut branches past the root collar, which insulates the tree's living trunk tissues from these pathogens



#### Seed planting

## Breeding methods

#### Cross-breeding
- Getting the male flower of one plant and the female flower of another
- Takes efforts to ensure that those two plants are crossing and no others
	- Use female but that's just about to open
	- Tie the male flower directly to the female flower
	- Put a bag around them to keep away other pollen


## Grafting
- Splicing a fruiting section of one plant with the main body of another plant
